%md

# Training a Random Forest to identify White Dwarf Stars

Uses the list of White Dwarf stars from https://arxiv.org/abs/1807.03315 - WD catalogue henceforth -  to train a Random Forest.
The method is similar to Section 5.8 from https://arxiv.org/abs/2012.02061 - GCNS henceforth. (GCNS = Gaia Catalogue of Nearby Stars)

def vector_to_array(col):
    def to_array_(v):
        return v.toArray().tolist()
    # Important: asNondeterministic requires Spark 2.3 or later
    # It can be safely removed i.e.
    # return udf(to_array_, ArrayType(DoubleType()))(col)
    # but at the cost of decreased performance
    return udf(to_array_, ArrayType(DoubleType())).asNondeterministic()(col)
    
    
def queryableSpuriousSources(filename):

                       .select(['source_id', 'prediction'] + [col("probability")[i] for i in range(2)])\

                        .select(['source_id', 'prediction', 'confidence'])\
                        .withColumnRenamed('prediction', 'is_good')
     
    QC_cuts.createOrReplaceTempView('dcr_spurious_sources')

paragraphs.text:
%spark.pyspark

# define the data source and select required columns
sqlContext.clearCache()

def initial_query(columns, how, limit = None, tablename = 'dcr_raw_sources', make_queryable = False, return_table = False):
    if how == 'NoLimit':
        raw_sources_df = spark.sql(f'SELECT {columns} FROM gaia_source')
    elif how == 'limited':
        raw_sources_df = spark.sql(f'SELECT {columns} FROM gaia_source \
                                        WHERE (1/parallax < limit)')
    elif how == 'sampled':
        sample_filter = f' WHERE MOD(source_id, {limit}) = 0'
        raw_sources_df = spark.sql(f'SELECT {columns} FROM gaia_source \
                                    {sample_filter}')

    else: raise NameError('how must equal: ["NoLimit", "limited"]')
    
    if make_queryable:
        raw_sources_df.createOrReplaceTempView(tablename)
        print(f'data at: {tablename}')
    if return_table:
        return raw_sources_df
        
def applyQualityControl(catalogue, QCcatalogue, threshold = 0.0, return_confidence = True):
    if return_confidence:
            cols = 'a.*, b.is_good, b.confidence'
    else:   cols = 'a.*'
    df = spark.sql(f'SELECT {cols} \
                FROM {catalogue} as a, \
                {QCcatalogue} as b\
                WHERE (b.source_id == a.source_id AND b.is_good == 1.0 AND b.confidence > {threshold})')
    return df
    
def addAbsoluteMag(df, passband = 'g'):
    return df.withColumn(f'm_{passband}', col(f'phot_{passband}_mean_mag') \
                             + 5.0*log10(col('parallax')/100))
        
def get_data(wd_filename, makeQueryable = 'dcr_raw_sources',
             qualityControl = False, limit = 5000, threshold = 0.0,
             addAbsolute = False, add_weighting = False):
    ''' Gets a subsample of eDR3 data and appends the wds. (labelled) '''
    
    # df = initial_query(columns = return_columns(how = 'str'), how = 'sampled', limit = limit, 
    #                     return_table = True)
    # df = df.select(return_columns()[:-1]).withColumn('is_wd', lit(0))
    # if add_weighting:
    #     df = df.withColumn('Pwd', lit(0))
    

    # open the WD catalogue and select required columns
    wd = sqlContext.read.format('com.databricks.spark.csv').options(
    header='true', inferschema='true').load(wd_filename)
    
    bad_wds = wd.filter((col('Pwd')<0.70))
    wd = wd.filter(col('Pwd')>0.75)
    # wd = wd.filter(col('parallax') > 0) # Change to extensive quality cut
    wd = wd.select(return_columns()).withColumn('is_wd', lit(1))
    bad_wds = bad_wds.select(return_columns()).withColumn('is_wd', lit(0))
    
    # df = df.union(wd.select(df.columns)) # Join WD's to background data ensuring matching column order
    df = wd.union(bad_wds.select(wd.columns))
    
    if addAbsolute:
        df = addAbsoluteMag(df = df, passband = 'g')
    
    if makeQueryable:
        print(f'data queryable from {makeQueryable}')
        df.createOrReplaceTempView(makeQueryable)
        
    print(df.columns)
        
    if qualityControl:
        if not makeQueryable:
            raise nameError('For quality control makeQueryable must be True')
        df = applyQualityControl(catalogue = makeQueryable, QCcatalogue = 'dcr_spurious_sources', threshold = threshold)
        df.createOrReplaceTempView(makeQueryable)
    return df
    
# limit = 5000, [3,164,528 sources with 265,678 WD's]
# limit = 5000, is_good, threshold == 0.5: [1,902,909 sources with XX WD's]
# limit = 5000, is_good, [1,902,909 sources with 242,443 WD's]

%spark.pyspark
def selectPlotType(x, y, plotType = 'scatter', ax = False, cmap = None, color = None,
                  label = None, s = 1, white_nan = False, bins = 100, cbar = True,
                  alpha = 1.0, cbarLabel = None, cbarShrink = 1.0, cbarLocation = None,
                  cbarPad = 0.15):
    if plotType == 'scatter':
        scatter(x, y, ax = ax,
                color = color, label = label, s = s, alpha = alpha)
    elif plotType == 'kdeHeatmap':
         kdeHeatmap(x, y, ax = ax, cmap = cmap, 
           white_nan = True, bins = bins, cbar = cbar)
           
    elif plotType == '2Dhist':
         hist2d(x,y, ax = ax, cmap = cmap, 
                white_nan = True, bins = bins, cbar = cbar, cbarPad = cbarPad,
                cbarLabel = cbarLabel, cbarShrink = cbarShrink, cbarLocation = cbarLocation)
                
    elif plotType == '2DhistSub':
         hist2dSubplots(x,y, ax = ax, cmap = cmap, 
           white_nan = True, bins = bins, cbar = cbar)
    else: raise nameError('plotType must be one of ["scatter", "kdeHeatmap", "2Dhist", 2DhistSub]')
        
def kdeHeatmap(x,y, ax = False, cmap = 'cividis', white_nan = False, bins = 100, cbar = True):
    '''creates a kdeHeatmap'''
    
    if not ax:
        ax = plt.figure(111)
    if white_nan:
        cmap = whiteNan(cmap)

    # Evaluate a gaussian kde on a regular grid of nbins x nbins over data extents
    nbins=bins
    k = kde.gaussian_kde([x,y])
    xi, yi = np.mgrid[x.min():x.max():nbins*1j, y.min():y.max():nbins*1j]
    zi = k(np.vstack([xi.flatten(), yi.flatten()]))

    # Make the plot
    im = ax.pcolormesh(xi, yi, zi.reshape(xi.shape), shading='auto', cmap = cmap)
    
#     if cbar:
#         add_colorbar(cmap = cmap, im = im)
    
def scatter(x,y, ax = False, color = None, label = None, s = 1, alpha = 1.0):
    '''creates a scatter plot'''
    if not ax:
        ax = plt.figure(111)
    ax.scatter(x, y, marker = '.', s = s, c = color, label = label, alpha = alpha)
    

def add_colorbar(cmap, im, label = None, shrink = 1.0, location = None, pad = 0.05):
    import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
    h = im[0]
    sm = plt.cm.ScalarMappable(cmap=cmap, norm=plt.Normalize(vmin=np.min(h), vmax=np.max(h)))
    plt.colorbar(sm,  label = label, shrink = shrink, location = location, pad = pad)
    
def hist2dSubplots(x,y, ax = False, cmap = 'cividis', white_nan = False, bins = 100, cbar = True):
    '''creates a 2dhist plot'''
    
    if not ax:
        ax = plt.figure(111)
    if white_nan:
        cmap = whiteNan(cmap)
    im = ax.hist2d(x, y, bins=bins, cmap=cmap)
    if cbar:
        addColorbarSubplots(cmap = cmap, im = im, ax = ax)

def addColorbarSubplots(cmap, im, ax):
    from mpl_toolkits.axes_grid1 import make_axes_locatable
    h = im[0]
    divider = make_axes_locatable(ax)
    cax = divider.append_axes('right', size='5%', pad=0.05)
    sm = plt.cm.ScalarMappable(cmap=cmap, norm=plt.Normalize(vmin=np.min(h), vmax=np.max(h)))
    plt.colorbar(sm, cax = cax)
    
    
def hist2d(x,y, ax = False, cmap = 'cividis', white_nan = False, bins = 100, cbar = True,
            cbarLabel = None, cbarShrink = 1.0, cbarLocation = None, cbarPad = 0.05):
    '''creates a 2dhist plot'''
    
    if not ax:
        ax = plt.figure(111)
    if white_nan:
        cmap = whiteNan(cmap)
    im = ax.hist2d(x, y, bins=bins, cmap=cmap)
    if cbar:
        add_colorbar(cmap = cmap, im = im, label = cbarLabel, shrink = cbarShrink, 
                     location = cbarLocation, pad = cbarPad)
    
def whiteNan(cmap):
    '''adds white base for colormaps'''
    
    from matplotlib import cm
    from matplotlib.colors import ListedColormap
    
    cmap = cm.get_cmap(cmap, 256)
    newcolors = cmap(np.linspace(0, 1, 256))
    white = np.array([1, 1, 1, 0])
    newcolors[:2, :] = white
    cmap = ListedColormap(newcolors)
    return cmap

%spark.pyspark
def CAMD(passbands, catalogue, classes, colors = ['k', 'darkred', 'darkblue'], ms = 1, 
         labels = None, plotType = 'scatter', cmap = 'cividis', bins = [100, 100], colorbar = True,
         limit = 10000, alpha = 1.0, save = False):
    '''plot an observational Hertzsprung-Russell diagram (aka colour / absolute magnitude diagram)
    for the unclassified sample to show the problem,
    include the photometric consistency filter to show the problem is astrometric in addition to photometric '''
    
    import matplotlib.pylab as plt
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize = (7.0, 9.0))
    
    quick_plot_filter = f' AND MOD(a.source_id, {limit}) = 0'
    tmp_df = spark.sql(f'SELECT a.phot_{passbands[0]}_mean_mag + 5.0*LOG10(a.parallax/100.0) \
                        AS m_{passbands[0]}, a.{passbands[1]}, a.is_wd FROM {catalogue} as a')
    # #                 {quick_plot_filter}')
    tmp_df = tmp_df.toPandas().dropna()

    for c, value in enumerate(classes):
        if type(ms) == list:
            s = ms[c]
        else: s = ms
        if type(labels) == type(None):
            label = value
        else: label = labels[c]
        color = None
        if plotType == 'scatter':
            color = colors[c]
        else: cmp = cmap[c]; bns = bins[c]

        tmp = tmp_df[tmp_df['is_wd'] == c]
        selectPlotType(x = tmp[f'{passbands[1]}'], y = tmp[f'm_{passbands[0]}'], 
                       plotType = plotType, ax = ax, cmap = cmp, color = color,
                       label = label, s = s, white_nan = True, bins = bns, cbar = colorbar)
        
    plt.ylim(18.0, -5.0)
    plt.xlim(-1, 2.0)
    plt.ylabel('Stellar brightness (absolute G magnitude) -->', fontsize = 16)
    plt.xlabel('<-- Stellar temperature (G - RP magnitude)', fontsize = 16)
    if plotType == 'scatter':
        lgnd = plt.legend(fontsize = 12, markerscale = 1)
    if save:
        if not dev_run:
            savefigs(save)

def spacialDistributionSubplotHex(class_val = 0, label = None, limit = None, labelCol = 'label', color = 'k', 
                                save = False, vmax = None, cmap = ['cividis', 'cividis'], bins = 100,
                                catalogue = 'dcr_training_sources', fontsize = 14, scale = [None, None]):

    if save:

def split_training_data(df, columns = '*', label = None, split = 0.8, seed = 0):
    '''splits df into trianing and test set. "label" [type int] creates a column for classification,
    if label is present set label = None'''
    
    # Select relevent columns
    df = df.select(columns)
    if label != None:
        df = df.withColumn('label', lit(label))
    # Split the data into train and test with seed for repeatability
    train, test = df.randomSplit([split, 1-split], seed)
    
    return train, test

train, test = split_training_data(df, columns = return_training_columns(),

%spark.pyspark
def transform_datasets(df, ignore = [], combine = True):
    '''combines two dataframes into a single transformed dataFrame for spark.ml 
    classifier for training or validation'''
    
    # Annotate and transform appropriate to the input required by the classifier's API.
    # Need a dataframe with labels and features: use vector assembler.
    assembler = VectorAssembler(inputCols=[i for i in df.columns if i not in ignore], 
                            outputCol = 'features', handleInvalid = 'skip')
    

    df = assembler.transform(df)
    return df

def dataSparkML(train, test, labelCol = 'labels', featuresCol = 'features', 
                normalise = False, scalerType = 'standard', save_normalization = False,
                nonFeatureCols = None):
    '''get train and test dataset for input using pyspark.ml'''
    
    train = transform_datasets(df=train, ignore = nonFeatureCols)
    test = transform_datasets(df = test, ignore = nonFeatureCols)
    
    if normalise:
        # We rename featuresCol to maintain col name for later analysis
        model = getScalerModel(train.withColumnRenamed(featuresCol, 'inputFeatures'),
                               scalerType = scalerType, featuresCol = 'inputFeatures', 
                               outCol = featuresCol, save = save_normalization)
        
        # Normalise each dataset with the training data distributions
        train = normaliseData(train.withColumnRenamed(featuresCol, 'inputFeatures'), model)
        test  = normaliseData( test.withColumnRenamed(featuresCol, 'inputFeatures'), model)
        print('data is normalised using training data distributions')
        # print(f'Training data = {train.count()} sources')
    
    return (train, test)
    
nonFeatureCols = ['is_wd', 'source_id', 'ra', 'dec', 'l', 'b', 'weighting']

%pyspark
# This cell does the business, given the data and training sets. Follows the example Python code at 
# https://spark.apache.org/docs/3.1.2/api/python/pyspark.ml.html#pyspark.ml.classification.RandomForestClassifier
# Weighting will become a feature after Spark 3.x is implimented

def train_model(save = False, weightCol = None):
    # instantiate a trained RF classifier, seeded for repeatability at this stage:
    rf = RandomForestClassifier(featureSubsetStrategy = 'sqrt', featuresCol = 'features', labelCol = 'is_wd',
                                numTrees = 100, impurity = 'entropy', maxDepth = 10, minInstancesPerNode = 1,
                                seed = 42)
    model = rf.fit(train)

    if save:
        if not dev_run:
            prefix_save = f'{user_home}/WD_detection/models/'
            print(f'{prefix_save}/{save}/')
            model.write().overwrite().save(f'{prefix_save}/{save}/randomForestClassifier/')
    return model
    
model = train_model(save = 'edr3_WDs_no_background', weightCol = 'weighting') # save = 'randomForest_WD_detection

def resCAMD(passbands, catalogues, colors = ['k', 'darkred', 'darkblue'], ms = 1, 
         labels = None, plotType = 'scatter', cmap = 'cividis', bins = [100, 100], colorbar = True,
         limit = 10000, alpha = 1.0, save = False, fontsize = 14):
    '''plot an observational Hertzsprung-Russell diagram (aka colour / absolute magnitude diagram)
    for the unclassified sample to show the problem,
    include the photometric consistency filter to show the problem is astrometric in addition to photometric '''
    
    import matplotlib.pylab as plt
    plt.rcParams['font.size'] = fontsize
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize = (9.0, 9.0))
    
    quick_plot_filter = f' AND MOD(a.source_id, {limit}) = 0'

    for c, catalogue in enumerate(catalogues):
        if type(ms) == list:
            s = ms[c]
        else: s = ms
        if type(labels) == type(None):
            label = catalogue
        else: label = labels[c]
        color = None
        
        if not type(plotType) == str:
            pType = plotType[c]
        else: pType = plotType
        
        if pType == 'scatter':
            color = colors[c]; cmp = None; bns = None
        else: cmp = cmap[c]; bns = bins[c]
        
        tmp = spark.sql(f'SELECT m_{passbands[0]}, {passbands[1]} FROM {catalogue}')
        
        tmp = tmp.toPandas().dropna()
        
        selectPlotType(x = tmp[f'{passbands[1]}'], y = tmp[f'm_{passbands[0]}'], 
                       plotType = pType, ax = ax, cmap = cmp, color = color,
                       label = label, s = s, white_nan = True, bins = bns, cbar = colorbar)
        
    plt.ylim(21.0, -3.0)
    plt.xlim(-1, 3)
    plt.ylabel('Stellar brightness (absolute G magnitude) -->', fontsize = fontsize)

def plot_probabilities(df, colors = ['darkblue', 'red'], bins = 25, alpha = 1.0,
                       label = ['class0', 'class1'], class_value = [0,1],
                      fontsize = 14, ec = 'k', save = False):
    '''histogram of the classification probabilities: cf. GCNS paper Figure 3'''

    plt.figure(1, figsize = (9.7, 6.0))

    dat['probability'] = [j[1] for j in dat['probability'].values]

    plt.hist(tmp, color = colors, bins=bins,
                           log = True, label = label, alpha = alpha, ec = ec)
    plt.xlabel('WD Probability -->', fontsize = fontsize)
    plt.ylabel('N', fontsize = fontsize)
    plt.xlim(0,1.0)
    plt.legend(label)
    if save:

paragraphs.title: Hyperparam Optimisation
paragraphs.text:
%spark.pyspark

from pyspark.ml.evaluation import BinaryClassificationEvaluator
from pyspark.ml.tuning import CrossValidator, ParamGridBuilder

rf = RandomForestClassifier(featureSubsetStrategy = 'sqrt', featuresCol = 'features',
                            labelCol = 'is_wd', seed=42) # Defines fixed parameters for tuning

# Provide the grid of training hyperparmas, this step is computationally expensive so limit the variables to best guesses and previously optimised models where possible.
grid = ParamGridBuilder()\
                 .addGrid(rf.impurity, ['entropy'])\
                    .addGrid(rf.minInstancesPerNode, [1])\
                        .addGrid(rf.numTrees, [100])\
                            .addGrid(rf.maxDepth, [10]).build()

def hyperparamOptimiser(grid, rf, train, test = None, parallelism = 5, numFolds = 5, ):
    
    evaluator = BinaryClassificationEvaluator().setLabelCol('is_wd')
    cv = CrossValidator(estimator=rf, estimatorParamMaps=grid, evaluator=evaluator,
                   parallelism=parallelism, numFolds=numFolds)
    cvModel = cv.fit(train)
    return cvModel.bestModel
    
bestModel = hyperparamOptimiser(grid = grid, rf = rf, train = train, numFolds = 4, parallelism = 6)

bestModel.extractParamMap()

%pyspark
def select_unlabelled_data(table, filename, featuresCol = 'features', sample = False,
                           normalise = False, scalerType = 'standard', features = '*',
                           linear_cut = True, labelCol = 'is_good'):
    '''selects full table to apply the trained model'''
    
    if sample: 
        quick_plot_filter = ' WHERE MOD(source_id, 10000) = 0'
    else: quick_plot_filter = ''
    
    # Get unlabelled data
    df = spark.sql(f'SELECT a.*, a.phot_g_mean_mag + 5.0*LOG10(a.parallax/100.0) \
                                         AS m_g, a.g_rp FROM {table} as a \
                                         {quick_plot_filter}')
    if linear_cut:
        df.filter(col('m_g') > 6 + 5*(col('phot_bp_mean_mag')-col('phot_rp_mean_mag')))
    
    # Assemble training features into DenseVector
    assembler = VectorAssembler(inputCols=features,
                                outputCol=featuresCol,
                                handleInvalid = 'keep')
                                
    df = assembler.transform(df)\
                .select(['source_id', 'm_g', 'g_rp', featuresCol])
                
    if normalise:
        # Scale the independent test data with a loaded scaler
        scaler = loadScaler(f'{filename}/{scalerType}_normalisation_model', scalerType = scalerType)
        df = normaliseData(df.withColumnRenamed(featuresCol, 'inputFeatures'), model = scaler)
        
    # Evaluate data with trained model
    rfModelRead = rfLoadModel(filepath = f'{filename}/randomForestClassifier')
    df = evaluateModel(rfModel = rfModelRead, df = df, normalise = True,  evaluate = False, 
                       labelCol = labelCol)
                       
    return df

%pyspark
def getResData(class_val = 0, label = None, limit = None, labelCol = 'label', color = 'k', 
                                save = False, sourceCat = 'gaia_source', vmax = None, projection = 'galactic',
                                trainingCat = 'dcr_training_sources', fontsize = 14, scale = None, bins = 100,
                                absPassbands = ['g']):

    plt.figure(2, figsize = (24.18, 7.0))
    plt.rcParams['font.size'] = fontsize
    
    # Allows a choice of projections.
    if projection == 'equitorial': coord_cols = ['ra', 'dec']
    elif projection == 'galactic': coord_cols = ['l', 'b']
    
    if limit == None:
        quick_plot_filter = f''
    elif type(limit) == int:
        quick_plot_filter = f' AND ((MOD(a.source_id, {limit}) = 0) or (b.{labelCol} == 1))' #  AND MOD (a.source_id, {limit/200}) = 0))'
    
    
    dat = spark.sql(f'SELECT b.{labelCol}, a.{coord_cols[0]}, a.{coord_cols[1]}, a.bp_rp, a.g_rp,\
                      a.phot_{absPassbands[0]}_mean_mag + 5.0*LOG10(a.parallax/100.0) \
                            AS m_{absPassbands[0]} FROM {sourceCat} as a, \
                                                 {trainingCat} as b \
                                                 WHERE a.source_id = b.source_id \
                                                 {quick_plot_filter} \
                                                 AND a.phot_{absPassbands[0]}_mean_mag + 5.0*LOG10(a.parallax/100.0) > 6 + 5*(a.bp_rp)') # Focuses on sources near the WD population
    dat = dat.withColumn(f'{coord_cols[0]}_rad', (col(coord_cols[0]) - 180.0) * np.pi / 180.0)\
                .withColumn(f'{coord_cols[1]}_rad', (col(coord_cols[1]) * np.pi / 180.0))\
                    .toPandas()
                    # .select([f'{coord_cols[0]}_rad', f'{coord_cols[1]}_rad', labelCol])\
                        
    return dat
    
def hexplot(dat, class_val = 0, label = None, labelCol = 'label', color = 'k', projection = 'galactic',
            save = False, vmax = None, fontsize = 14, scale = None, bins = 100, cmap = ['inferno', 'cividis']):
            
    plt.figure(2, figsize = (24.18, 7.0))
    plt.rcParams['font.size'] = fontsize
    
    if projection == 'equitorial': coord_cols = ['ra', 'dec']
    elif projection == 'galactic': coord_cols = ['l', 'b']
    
    for i, value in enumerate(class_val):
        tmp = dat[dat[labelCol] == value]
        plt.subplot(1,2,i+1, projection='aitoff')
        plt.grid(True)
        if vmax:
            vm = vmax[i]; extend = 'max'
        else: vm = None; extend = None
        plt.title(f'{label[i]}', fontsize = fontsize+4)
        image = plt.hexbin(tmp[f'{coord_cols[0]}_rad'].values, tmp[f'{coord_cols[1]}_rad'].values, cmap=cmap[i], 
                   gridsize=bins, mincnt=1, bins=scale, vmax = vm, alpha = 1.0) 
        cb = plt.colorbar(image, extend = extend, spacing = 'proportional') 
    plt.tight_layout()
    if save:
        if not dev_run:
            savefigs(save)
    plt.show()
